As others have commented, any program that fails to do a case-independent
match of host names is buggy.  The preference for uppercase or lowercase has
its roots in religion, Model 33 Teletypes (need I say that both camps accuse
the other of "Model 33 Teletype wedgeness"?), and individual perceptions of
what is esthetically pleasing.

I for one bristle at Unix systems which impose "mrc" as my login name; as
initials of a proper name, it should be "MRC".  Some organizations may feel
that their trademarks are compromised if their corporate acronym isn't shown
in "correct" case in examples of their host name originating from one of
their systems.

Most of us would be terribly bent out of shape if a remote mailer returned
mail because the case was wrong.

Use case-independent comparisons, friends!

-- Mark --

